args: Yes, and by no small miracle.
She is undergoing treatment as we speak.\nShe's going to be fine.
Your usual visitor should be around shortly.
Ah, here he is now.\nCome in.
Thank you. It does me well to see you\nawake, Elisanne.
He was the one who brought you here.
He thought it too dangerous to take you\nto the Church, considering recent events.\nAnd he has visited you without fail each—
Yes, well. Credit where it's due.
Now, I shall go tell the others that\nyou're awake.
I'm sure you two have plenty to discuss.
...Thank you, Tobias. I owe you my life.
I'm not so sure of that.
It was I who sent you into that trap,\nafter all.

These are turbulent times. Those who
cling to the past and refuse to engage
with current discourse cannot save
anyone.
And I thought if we simply silenced the\nconservatives' talisman...
...No. No, in truth I merely succumbed to\nmy own selfish desires.
The cardinal claimed that with you gone,\nI would be named the next Grand Paladyn.

But after sending you to your death,
I found myself questioning whether
killing you would truly benefit the
Church.
So you came to my rescue.
Indeed. Oh, Elisanne... I'm so sorry.
It is in the past now.
What? This is your LIFE we're talking\nabout! You have more than just cause\nto punish me.
Julietta and I are both alive.\nThat is all that matters.
Besides, it can't have been easy for you\nto act against the cardinal's orders.
You had much more to lose than you did\nto gain.
And yet nonetheless you came, and we're\nalive because of it. You have my gratitude\nfor that.
Heh, maybe so. How have things been\nat the Church in the days since?
There has been no mention of the events\non the Rendahm Road. I imagine that\nwas the plan from the start.
Here now, it's not like the perditionists\nhave a monopoly on corruption.\nThe conservatives are—
Don't worry, I know how prolifically\ncorruption exists in our world.

Until recently I had been too blind to see
it—or perhaps too unwilling. But from here
on, I will decide on my own definition of
justice.
I will no longer be led by the hand like\na child. My job now is to guide.
I shall leave the perditionists to you,\nTobias.
I imagine there are still plenty among\nyour allies who distrust me.
Such people are unlikely to listen,\nregardless of my message.
But you can unify them. Lead them towards\nyour ideal.
I'll do whatever I can to support you,\nbut it remains to be seen how much\nthat will actually be.
Do you really believe me capable?\nAs you said, my position within my\nfaction is not exactly stable at present.
I do. You have a dream, and you mustn't\ngive up on it here.
You're willing to hear and consider all\nperspectives—which was the original\nideal of the perditionists.
Yet we chose to drive out the old guard\nthrough any means, while you strove\nto include everyone.
I might actually be glad you were\nchosen as Grand Paladyn.
Yes. I'll give it my all as well, of course—\njust in service to my own beliefs.
In the end, though, we'll both be working\ntoward making everyone happy.
Our future is in your hands, Grand Paladyn.
I will do all I can to light the way forward.
(This sacred white armor I wear is no\ndoubt destined to be stained by blood\non the path ahead.)
(But I will not falter. I will continue to lead\nthe way with my head held high.)
(I will become light itself, even if it\ncosts me my very soul.)
